-# Whop Skill Execution Integration PRD
-
-**Date:** 2026-05-03
-**Status:** Draft
-**Owner:** Codex
-**Scope:** `agent_workflows/whop_auto/`
-**Phase:** Post-foundation implementation phase after status discovery and audited dispatch primitives
-
-## Summary
-
-The next development phase is to turn the existing autonomy primitives into executable skill flows for `whop-adopt`, `whop-deploy`, and `whop-reconcile`. The current codebase can classify risk, build durable consent events, append audited dispatch events, sanitize remote state, and read live Whop/Vercel status. It does not yet execute the core skill flows through one shared runner that emits `intent`, `consent`, `dispatched`, `observed`, `divergence`, and `finalized` events around real remote operations.
-
-This phase delivers that integration layer. It stops short of `whop-scaffold`, `whop-manage`, and `whop-market`, which are separate feature phases.
-
-## Problem
-
-`agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/` now contains the necessary primitives, but they are still disconnected:
-
-- [executor.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/executor.ts:170) can validate and audit a single consent-gated dispatch.
-- [status.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/status.ts:61) can produce live status with meaningful terminal states.
-- [index.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/index.ts:104) exposes low-level tools and read-only status collection.
-
-What is missing is the runtime path that uses those pieces to:
-
-- derive a concrete action list for adopt/deploy/reconcile,
-- enforce consent before every gated remote mutation,
-- emit `observed` and `finalized` events after real tool execution,
-- reuse or reject prior consent on resume,
-- stop safely on `ambiguous-target`, `payload-changed`, `blocked-by-policy`, and `unknown-remote-state`.
-
-Without that layer, the project has correct building blocks but no end-to-end skill execution.
-
-## Goal
-
-Build the first executable autonomy runner for the Phase 1 skills:
-
-- `whop-adopt`
-- `whop-deploy`
-- `whop-reconcile`
-
-The runner must use the existing audited executor path and existing transport/tool boundaries, not a parallel control flow.
-
-## Non-Goals
-
-- No implementation of `whop-scaffold`, `whop-manage`, or `whop-market`.
-- No new undocumented Whop or Vercel APIs.
-- No production-side destructive cleanup automation beyond what current policy already permits.
-- No credential rotation flows.
-- No LLM planner or critic integration beyond deterministic local runner behavior.
-- No broad refactor of unrelated workflow folders or vendored code.
-
-## Users
-
-- Omar invoking Whop automation against a real adopted repo.
-- Future agents that need one executable control path instead of disconnected helper functions.
-
-## Current Baseline
-
-Already implemented and verified:
-
-- Read-only status discovery with live Whop/Vercel reads and sanitized remote state.
-- Durable consent event construction and payload-hash reuse checks.
-- Policy-based risk classification.
-- Audited dispatch helper that blocks mutation until `consent` and `dispatched` are appended.
-- Clean Node 20 runtime gate with `npm ci`, `npx tsc --noEmit`, `npm run build`, and `npm test`.
-
-Still missing:
-
-- Schema support for `divergence` events in the runner-facing event model.
-- Runner-facing state coverage for the D3 adopt/deploy/reconcile terminal and blocking states.
-- Action planning for adopt/deploy/reconcile.
-- Evented mutation orchestration around real tool calls.
-- Resume-aware `observed` and `finalized` event handling.
-- Skill-facing entrypoints above the low-level MCP tools.
-
-## Functional Requirements
-
-### 1. Shared skill runner
-
-Create one local execution path that:
-
-- takes a resolved target repo,
-- runs status discovery first,
-- derives a deterministic action sequence,
-- validates that every action has `stepId`, `capabilityId`, `toolId`, `riskClass`, `idempotencyKey`, and `requires_consent`,
-- routes every mutating remote action through the audited executor path,
-- appends `observed` after successful re-read or response capture,
-- appends `divergence` when proof cannot be established, payload changed, ownership mismatches, or targets are ambiguous,
-- appends `finalized` only when the terminal state is actually reached.
-
-Every successful `dispatched` step must end in exactly one of:
-
-- `observed`
-- `divergence`
-- a terminal blocked/unknown outcome that is itself recorded
-
-The runner must not leave silent hanging `dispatched` steps.
-
-### 2. `whop-deploy` integration
-
-`whop-deploy` must:
-
-- no-op when current production already matches `HEAD`,
-- require exact deploy consent for public-visible promotion and iframe update,
-- use Git push plus Vercel Git-linked deployment observation by SHA as the only deployment mechanism in this phase,
-- update manifest deploy metadata only after Vercel and Whop agree,
-- stop on changed SHA, changed app/project/domain target, or unreadable remote state.
-
-This phase does not add a new `vercel.deployments.create` wrapper. Deployment creation is inferred from Git push plus Vercel linkage, then proven through `listDeployments` and `waitForDeployment`.
-
-### 3. `whop-adopt` integration
-
-`whop-adopt` must:
-
-- reuse existing status detection,
-- stop on ambiguous app or project matches,
-- create or repair missing env/webhook state only through audited mutation steps,
-- write manifest and registry only after verified ownership,
-- preserve the existing happy path already covered by integration tests.
-
-### 4. `whop-reconcile` integration
-
-`whop-reconcile` must:
-
-- classify drift into safe local repair, consent-required repair, or blocked,
-- perform safe manifest/registry repair locally without redundant consent,
-- stop on ambiguous target selection,
-- route any public-visible or destructive repair through the audited executor path,
-- preserve `unknown-remote-state` as a terminal stop, not a silent retry loop.
-
-### 5. Event lifecycle completeness
-
-For all three skills:
-
-- append `intent` before execution begins,
-- append `consent` before every gated mutation,
-- append `dispatched` before the actual mutation callback,
-- append `observed` after the system can prove remote state,
-- append `divergence` on payload change, ambiguous targets, owner mismatch, or missing observed state,
-- append `finalized` only on true terminal completion.
-
-The event schema for this phase must explicitly support `divergence` with:
-
-- `runId`
-- `skill`
-- `stepId`
-- `capabilityId`
-- `toolId`
-- `expectedPayloadHash`
-- `observedPayloadHash`
-- `observedDigestHash`
-- `divergenceClass`
-- `redactedReason`
-- `terminalState`
-- `at`
-
-`divergence` must remain sanitized. Raw provider errors, raw free text, webhook URLs, and secret values are forbidden.
-
-### 6. Resume behavior
-
-Resume must:
-
-- reuse consent only when payload hash matches,
-- reject stale consent with `payload-changed`,
-- re-read remote state before replaying non-idempotent creates,
-- surface `unknown-remote-state` rather than guessing when remote proof is unavailable.
-
-## Required Schema and Policy Alignment
-
-Before runner integration begins, the codebase must align the foundational schemas and risk policy with this phase:
-
-- Add `divergence` to the runtime event schema.
-- Expand the runner-facing state enum to cover the D3 states needed by `whop-adopt`, `whop-deploy`, and `whop-reconcile`, including:
-  - `deploy-status-ready`
-  - `deploy-noop-current`
-  - `deploy-consent-required`
-  - `deploy-blocked`
-  - `reconcile-complete`
-  - `ambiguous-target`
-  - `consent-required`
-  - `blocked-by-policy`
-- Fix risk classification so local tools with `LOCAL-*` capability IDs classify as:
-  - `riskClass: "local-write"`
-  - `requiresConsent: false`
-  - `blocked: false`
-
-Local manifest, registry, event-log, and codegen operations must not be accidentally gated as remote private updates.
-
-## MCP Entry Points
-
-This phase must expose strict high-level skill entrypoints rather than only low-level transport tools.
-
-Minimum MCP entrypoints:
-
-- `whop.deploy`
-  - `targetRepo: string`
-  - `branch?: string`
-  - `productionDomain?: string`
-  - `runId?: string`
-- `whop.adopt`
-  - `targetRepo: string`
-  - `appIdHint?: string`
-  - `vercelProjectIdHint?: string`
-  - `runId?: string`
-- `whop.reconcile`
-  - `targetRepo: string`
-  - `dryRun?: boolean`
-  - `forceReconcile?: boolean`
-  - `runId?: string`
-
-`index.ts` must stay thin, but the tool schemas must be explicit and validated.
-
-## Technical Approach
-
-Recommended approach:
-
-Build a thin skill runner on top of the existing low-level modules instead of embedding more logic into `index.ts` or duplicating dispatch rules inside each skill.
-
-This means:
-
-- keep policy in [executor.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/executor.ts:103),
-- keep state discovery in [status.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/status.ts:61),
-- add a new execution module for skill flows,
-- keep MCP server wiring thin and declarative.
-
-Rejected alternative:
-
-- Put all skill logic directly into [index.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/index.ts:1).
-
-Reason:
-
-- it would mix transport wiring, orchestration, policy, and persistence in one file and make resume logic harder to test.
-
-Rejected alternative:
-
-- Implement `whop-scaffold` at the same time as adopt/deploy/reconcile.
-
-Reason:
-
-- scaffold introduces a larger remote-create surface and a separate launch consent model. It is a different phase.
-
-## File Boundaries
-
-Expected primary files in this phase:
-
-- Modify: [executor.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/executor.ts:1)
-- Create: `agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/runner.ts`
-- Create or modify: skill-specific action/plan modules under `agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/`
-- Modify: [index.ts](/C:/Users/albak/xdev/Claude_Code_Automations/agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/src/index.ts:1)
-- Modify tests under `agent_workflows/whop_auto/bin/whop-state-mcp/test/`
-
-## Success Criteria
-
-This phase is complete when:
-
-- runtime schemas and risk policy are aligned with the D3/D6 requirements for this phase,
-- `whop-adopt`, `whop-deploy`, and `whop-reconcile` all have executable runner paths.
-- Every mutating action goes through the shared audited dispatch helper.
-- every successful `dispatched` event is followed by `observed` or `divergence`,
-- `observed`, `divergence`, and `finalized` events are emitted in the correct order,
-- Resume and stale-consent scenarios are covered by tests.
-- No-op deploy, safe local reconcile, and ambiguous-target stops are verified.
-- `npm ci`, `npx tsc --noEmit`, `npm run build`, and `npm test` pass in `agent_workflows/whop_auto` from a platform-local Node 20 install in the intended shell.
-
-## Risks
-
-- The project may accidentally grow two orchestration layers if runner logic leaks back into `index.ts`.
-- Reconcile can become too permissive if safe local repair and consent-required repair are not sharply separated.
-- Remote `observed` logic can become optimistic if it trusts responses instead of re-reads for non-idempotent creates.
-- Runner state names can drift from the documented D3 state model unless the schema alignment task happens first.
-- The implementation can accidentally build the wrong deployment path if Git-push-triggered deployment and API-created deployment are both implied.
-
-## Phase Boundary
-
-This PRD ends at executable Phase 1 skill integration.
-
-The next phase after this PRD is:
-
-- scaffold creation flow,
-- then broader manage/market execution surfaces.
